506.title: Natural numbers: Intro to Number Sets
506.clickbait: Natural numbers are the numbers we use to count in everyday life.
506.text:
> *God created the natural numbers. All else is the work of man.*  
> — Leopold Kronecker %%note: Technically he said God created the *integers* ("die ganzen Zahlen" in German), but negative quantities are arguably the work of man as well.%%

The natural numbers is a fancy name for the numbers we use to count things, starting from 1, 2, 3, and so on.

These are the numbers we first learn as children, and are the numbers we are most familiar with to actually be _numbers_. Have you ever had someone tell you that zero wasn't a number? Or that negative numbers didn't really exist, we just use them as a convenient shorthand for owing people things? The fact that these numbers tend to make sense to our heads without any sort of special mental training means they're called the natural numbers.


## Why are number sets important?

Before we go any further, it would be nice to know the motivation behind defining the number sets first.

A [3jz set] is a fancy name for a collection of objects. Some collections of objects have special properties — such as the set of all blue things, which are special in that they're all blue. In math, if a set of objects all have a certain property, we can make **inferences** about them — that is, there are certain things we can say about them that you can deduce logically. For example:

> In a [481 field], every nonzero number has a multiplicative inverse.

You don't need to know what a field is yet (it's a special type of set), but now you can make inferences about them without restricting yourself to a specific example when talking about them. For example, you know that if a set _is_ a field, then every number in that set that isn't zero can divide into another number in that set (by multiplying by its "multiplicative inverse") and produce yet another number in that set.

Conversely, you can also tell when a set is or isn't a field based on whether it satisfies the properties a field has. For example, since you can't divide $3$ by $2$ (because the result is $1.5$ which is not a natural number), you now know that the natural numbers are not a field.


## The set of natural numbers

So with this in mind, we can define the set of natural numbers as the numbers we get by starting from $1$ and counting up as far as is theoretically possible. We'll notate the set as $\{1, 2, 3, \ldots\}$. When doing set theory, however, mathematicians tend to prefer to start from $0$ instead. We'll see why in a moment.

We just mentioned that a set has properties that can be used. What properties do the natural numbers have?

Before we get into that, let's create some notation we'll use. If you have a natural number $n$, then $n_c$ will denote "the number you get after you count up from $n$". So $2_c$ is $3$, $59_c$ is $60$, $9287_c$ is $9288$, and so on. We can also string together a bunch of $c$'s to denote counting up twice, three times, etc., for example: $2_{ccc}$ is $5$.

### Natural numbers can be put in order

The first thing we usually notice is that certain numbers are bigger than others. The rule for this is very simple: if you can count up from one number to get to another number, the first number is _less than_ the second number. We write this as: $n < m$ if we can write $m$ as $n_{ccccc...}$ for some number of $c$'s.

So because $5 = 2_{ccc}$, we know that $2 < 5$.

### There is always a first natural number in any collection of them %%note: Mathematicians call this the well-ordering property.%%

The natural numbers not only can be put all into order, any subset of them can also be put in order from smallest to largest, and be guaranteed to have that order _start_ from somewhere. For example, the set of all even natural numbers, which would be $\{2, 4, 6, 8, \ldots\}$ can be said to _start from_ the number $2$.

### Natural numbers can be added

From here, we will start defining _operations_ on the numbers, which are procedures you can perform on them.

To add two natural numbers, take the number of times the first number was counted up from zero and count the second number up the same number of times. To find out $4 + 3$, note that $4 = 0_{cccc}$, so $4 + 3 = 3_{cccc} = 7$.

Saying that natural numbers can be added is to say that this procedure always works (as in it always gives us another natural numbers).

### Natural numbers can be multiplied

To multiply two natural numbers, take the number of times the first number was counted up from zero, and _add_ the second number to zero the same number of times. AS in the addition example, to find out $4 \times 3$, note that $4 = 0_{cccc}$, so $4 \times 3 = 0 + 3 + 3 + 3 + 3 = 12$.

This is another way of saying "multiplication is repeated addition", but the important thing is that this procedure is another one that always works.

### Natural numbers cannot always be divided

This might seem like a _lack_ of a property at first, but having numbers that might not necessarily divide other numbers leads to interesting properties that can be analyzed. For example, it leads to the existence of [4mf prime numbers]. In a set of numbers where every number can divide into every other number (a field, as we mentioned above), there are no primes.

### Natural numbers cannot always be subtracted

For example, "you can't take $3$ from $2$; $2$ is less than $3$" — to quote a [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DfCJgC2zezw Tom Lehrer song] about the New Math.

This is actually one of the ways you can define "less than" on the natural numbers. One natural number is _less than_ another if you cannot subtract the second natural number from the first.

If you want numbers to always be subtractable, then you'll need a set bigger than just the natural numbers — you'll need to extend it into the [-integers], which is what the next article is all about.
